  "local_port": 34150,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do you sort a collection in Java?",
  "response": "In Java, you can sort a collection using various methods depending on the type of collection you are working with. Here are some common ways to sort collections:\n\n### Sorting a List\n\nIf you have a `List`, you can use the `Collections.sort()` method or utilize the `List.sort()` method.\n\n#### Using `Collections.sort()`\n\n```java\nimport java.util.*;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        List<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList(5, 3, 8, 1, 2));\n        \n        // Sort the list using Collections.sort()\n        Collections.sort(list);\n        \n        System.out.println(list); // Output: [1, 2, 3, 5, 8]\n    }\n}\n```\n\n#### Using `List.sort()`\n\n```java\nimport java.util.*;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        List<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList(5, 3, 8, 1, 2));\n        \n        // Sort the list using List.sort()\n        list.sort(Comparator.naturalOrder());\n        \n        System.out.println(list); // Output: [1, 2, 3, 5, 8]\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Sorting a Custom Object List\n\nIf you are sorting a list of custom objects, you need to provide a `Comparator`.\n\n```java\nimport java.util.*;\n\nclass Person {\n    String name;\n    int age;\n\n    Person(String name, int age) {\n        this.name = name;\n        this.age = age;\n    }\n\n    @Override\n    public String toString() {\n        return name + \" (\" + age + \")\";\n    }\n}\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        List<Person> people = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList(\n            new Person(\"Alice\", 30),\n            new Person(\"Bob\", 25),\n            new Person(\"Charlie\", 35)\n        ));\n        \n        // Sort by age using a custom Comparator\n        people.sort(Comparator.comparingInt(person -> person.age));\n        \n        System.out.println(people); // Output: [Bob (25), Alice (30), Charlie (35)]\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Sorting a Set\n\nFor a `Set`, you can convert it to a `List`, sort it, and then convert it back if necessary.\n\n```java\nimport java.util.*;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        Set<Integer> set = new HashSet<>(Arrays.asList(5, 3, 8, 1, 2));\n        \n        // Convert set to list\n        List<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>(set);\n        \n        // Sort the list\n        Collections.sort(list);\n        \n        System.out.println(list); // Output: [1, 2, 3, 5, 8]\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Sorting a Map by Keys or Values\n\nMaps cannot be directly sorted, but you can sort them by keys or values by converting the entries to a list.\n\n#### Sorting by Keys\n\n```java\nimport java.util.*;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        Map<String, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();\n        map.put(\"Apple\", 3);\n        map.put(\"Orange\", 2);\n        map.put(\"Banana\", 1);\n        \n        // Convert map keys to list and sort\n        List<String> sortedKeys = new ArrayList<>(map.keySet());\n        Collections.sort(sortedKeys);\n        \n        // Create a sorted map\n        Map<String, Integer> sortedMap = new LinkedHashMap<>();\n        for (String key : sortedKeys) {\n            sortedMap.put(key, map.get(key));\n        }\n        \n        System.out.println(sortedMap); // Output: {Apple=3, Banana=1, Orange=2}\n    }\n}\n```\n\n#### Sorting by Values\n\n```java\nimport java.util.*;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        Map<String, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();\n        map.put(\"Apple\", 3);\n        map.put(\"Orange\", 2);\n        map.put(\"Banana\", 1);\n        \n        // Convert map entries to list and sort by value\n        List<Map.Entry<String, Integer>> sortedEntries = new ArrayList<>(map.entrySet());\n        sortedEntries.sort(Map.Entry.comparingByValue());\n        \n        // Create a sorted map\n        Map<String, Integer> sortedMap = new LinkedHashMap<>();\n        for (Map.Entry<String, Integer> entry : sortedEntries) {\n            sortedMap.put(entry.getKey(), entry.getValue());\n        }\n        \n        System.out.println(sortedMap); // Output: {Banana=1, Orange=2, Apple=3}\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThese are some of the common ways to sort collections in Java. Depending on the specific requirements and the type of collection, you can choose the appropriate method.",
